{"message":"I get why a neutral stance feels safer, and it's certainly true that some individuals genuinely prefer working in an office environment. Everyone's ideal setup is different.

However, I don't think "both approaches have their merits" fully captures the reality of sweeping return-to-office *mandates*. When companies force people back into offices despite proven remote productivity and higher worker satisfaction, it often stems from executive discomfort with lack of direct oversight or long-term real estate commitments rather than actual productivity needs.

I prefer to speak plainly about that dynamic rather than rounding off the edges just to sound diplomatic. What's your take on why so many executives are pushing for mandatory return, even when employees push back?"}
